  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Post-Cyclone Mora WASH Infrastructure Rehabilitation</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">This project seeks to ensure access to equitable and safe sanitation facilities in 3 IDP camps in Sittwe township and 1 in Myebon, all of which suffered significant latrine damages from Cyclone Mora on 30 May 2017. DRC, CDN and RI will repair and upgrade 470 latrines to a more cyclone resistant design which will be shared and endorsed by the Rakhine WASH Cluster, thereby mitigating risks of groundwater contamination, further cyclone impact on latrines and public health outbreaks for 20,258 IDPs. 

To ensure equitable access for different groups, certain latrines will be modified to accommodate Persons with (a) Disability/ies (PWD) and the elderly through peer groups and focus group discussions, and child-friendly latrine designs will be developed by working with a peer group of children. Tech briefs will be developed documenting the design processes and the result for sharing with the WASH Cluster. Women and girls are disproportionately burdened by lack of safe sanitation facilities: they are at high risk of gender-based violence when they seek alternative sanitation practices, and are unable to practice safe menstrual hygiene. Based on consultation with women, it has been decided to distribute torches to increase safe access to latrines for women and children at night, locks are included in latrine designs for privacy, dignity and safety, and gender segregated latrines will be restored.  

To further enhance the positive environmental impact of sanitation facilities, this project will also repair 2 waste incinerators in 2 IDP camps.</narrative>
  </description>
